1 Learning objectives

  1. You will use dplyr::summarize() to extract summary statistics from the data.

  2. You will know how to summarize over multiple variables using dplyr::across().

  3. You will use dplyr::group_by() to group variables before performing operations or transformations on them.

  4. You will know how to use dplyr::count() as a handy function to count groups.

2 The Yaounde COVID-19 dataset

In this lesson, we will again use the data from the COVID-19 serological survey conducted in Yaounde, Cameroon.

yaounde <- read_csv(here::here('ch04_data_wrangling/data/yaounde_data.csv'))
## a smaller subset of variables
yao <- yaounde %>% select(neighborhood, is_smoker, occupation, 
                          treatment_combinations, symptoms, 
                          age, sex, weight_kg, height_cm, 
                          igg_result)
yao

See the previous lesson for more information about this data.

3 Small data cleaning using what you’ve learnt!

Here you can see a combination of the use of dplyr::filter() and dplyr::across(). The goal is to remove any entries that are NA for the variables is_smoker, sex, igg_result.

As a second step, using dplyr::mutate(), we want to make sure these variables are factors.

yao <- yao %>%
  filter(across(.cols = c(is_smoker, sex, igg_result), 
                .fns = ~ !is.na(.x))) %>%
  mutate(across(.cols = c(is_smoker, sex, igg_result),
                .fns = as.factor))

4 Introducing dplyr::summarize()

dplyr::summarize() creates a new data frame with the desired summary statistics (mean, standard deviation, etc.)

4.1 Basic summarizing operations

  • Looking at the center of a distribution: mean mean(), median median()

  • Looking at the spread of a distribution: standard deviation sd(), interquartile rangeIQR(), median absolute deviation mad()

  • Looking at the range of a distribution: minimum min(), maximum max(), quantiles q25(), q50(), q75(), quantile()

  • Finding the position within a variable: first element first(), last element last(), element number n `nth()`

  • Counting a variable: count all elements (including repetitions) n(), count all distinct elements n_distinct()

  • Applying a logical to a variable: include any any(), include all all()

Let’s learn all we can about the age distribution in our dataset!

yao %>% 
summarise(
    n = n(),
    q25 = quantile(age, .25, na.rm = TRUE),
    q50 = quantile(age, .50, na.rm = TRUE),
    q75 = quantile(age, .75, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_age = mean(age, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_age  = sd(age, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_age = min(age, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_age = max(age, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

na.rm = TRUE removes NA values, a useful option, as NA values would lead to the summary statistic also being equal to NA.

Summarize the variable weight_kg into quartiles (q25, q50, q75)

5 Summarizing over multiple variables using dplyr::across()

If you missed it, see the introduction to across in the dplyr::mutate() lesson!

Here let’s see how to apply multiple summarizing operations, the mean and the standard deviation (list(mean = mean, sd = sd)) on multiple variables at the same time, on age and weight, while specifying how these summary variables should be named (.names = "{.col}.{.fn}"): .col references the name of the column and .fn the name of the function).

yao %>%
  summarise(across(c(age, weight_kg), 
                   list(mean = mean, sd = sd),
                   .names = "{.col}.{.fn}"))

Instead of doing by name you can also summarize across multiple variables using conditions.

where(is.numeric) conveniently allows to get the summary statistic over all numeric variables in the dataset. (In our case, this would be the variables of age and weight, we are not manipulating other numeric variables.)

yao %>%
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric), mean, na.rm = TRUE))

What is the average weight and height (across) of informal workers who were IgG positive? Put in a dataframe with the two columns of weight_kg and height_cm.

6 Introducing dplyr::group_by()

dplyr::group_by() allows to **group by** a variable and then perform operations “by groups” in this variable.

Use dplyr::ungroup() as soon as you are done with your operations per groups, otherwise the data will remain grouped when you use it in the future. This can lead to coding or analysis errors.

6.1 Classical structure of dplyr::group_by()

We can use dplyr::group_by() on the treatment combinations in the dataset to know how many of each kind were received by the patients. dplyr::group_by() “lumps” together all the identical treatments and summarize(N=n()) counts each unique treatment and puts this count in a new column N. Of high importance, we ungroup at the end of our operation, else the data will remain “lumped” together by treatments.

dplyr::arrange() is a useful dplyr function to view the data in an organized function. desc has been introduced in the dplyr::mutate() lesson: it arranges the variable from its largest to smallest value.

yao %>%
  group_by(treatment_combinations) %>%
  summarize(N=n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(desc(N))

What is the average weight of all smoker options in the questionnaire?

6.2 Nested Groupings

We can group by several variables. Grouping by several variables consists in making groups based on the different unique combinations of each of these variables. Here, we are looking at medians and standard deviations of the age of all the individual combinations for smokers, gender, and positive or negative IgG results. dplyr::group_by() creates all the unique combinations (for example: “Smoker-Male-Positive” or “Smoker-Female-Negative” etc.) and dplyr::summarize() calculates the groups’ median and standard deviation.

yao %>%
  group_by(is_smoker, sex, igg_result) %>%
  summarize(age_median = median(age, na.rm = TRUE),
            age_std = sd(age, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()

When you are grouping by a factors’ variable, you need to add the argument .drop = FALSE in your dpylr::group_by() call to see your subsequent operation on empty groups (i.e. combinations that do not exist).

For example, if you look for the combination “Smoker-Female-Positive”, you will find that it is absent from the grouping and subsequent summarizing operation. This is because this combination does not exist. If you want to have it included (with an age and standard deviation as NA ) then you need to set .drop=FALSE

yao %>%
  group_by(is_smoker, sex, igg_result) %>%
  summarize(age_median = median(age, na.rm = TRUE),
            age_std = sd(age, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(is_smoker=="Smoker", 
         sex=="Female",
         igg_result=="Positive")

You can see the difference below. When setting .drop=FALSE

yao %>%
  group_by(is_smoker, sex, igg_result, .drop = FALSE) %>%
  summarize(age_median = median(age, na.rm = TRUE),
            age_std = sd(age, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(is_smoker=="Smoker", 
         sex=="Female",
         igg_result=="Positive")

Let’s have a look at some statistics for IgG results grouped by sex and neighborhood. We will be looking at some statistics for the weight_kg variable: the interquartile range (weight_IQR) and the median (weight_median). Base yourself on the example above (i.e. removing NAs with na.rm=TRUE and not dropping any groups during the grouping .drop=FALSE).

6.3 See your grouping variables

In the eventuality where you are getting weird results in your data, that your wrangling is 500 lines of code, and that you may have forgotten an ungroup , it could be useful to check by what variables your data is currently grouped. You can do this with dplyr::group_vars().

yao %>%
  group_by(igg_result, sex) %>%
  group_by(igg_result, age) %>%
  group_vars()

If you grouped the data by one variable and then call again dpylr::group_by() with another variable, dpylr::group_by() overrides the previous grouping by default. To add an additional grouping to an ALREADY GROUPED dataset, you can call dpylr::group_by() with the .add = TRUE argument.

For example, if you wanted to add a grouping by age to our initial grouping you would write:

yao %>%
  group_by(igg_result, sex) %>%
  group_by(age, .add=TRUE) %>%
  group_vars()

7 Introducing dplyr::count()

The dplyr::count() function wraps a bunch of things into one beautiful friendly line of code to help you find counts of observations by group.

Let’s use dplyr::count() on our occupation variable. Please note, doing count(occupation) is the same as doing group_by(occupation) %>% summarize(n()) (as we did above for treatment combinations).

yao %>%
  count(occupation)

We can also apply dplyr::count() in a nested fashion.

yao %>%
  count(occupation, sex)

Count how many women did not have symptoms? Use count and then filter to only have the results for women.
